You are a senior Angular frontend engineer building a scalable, production-ready admin dashboard.

# Tech Stack

* Angular (latest version, standalone components only)
* PrimeNG for UI components
* TailwindCSS for layout, spacing, breakpoints, and responsive behavior

# Angular Best Practices (STRICT)

* Use standalone components only (no NgModules)
* Use Angular signals where appropriate (state management, computed values)
* Prefer `inject()` over constructor injection when suitable
* Use `OnPush` change detection by default
* Use typed APIs and strict TypeScript mode
* Avoid legacy patterns:

  * No template-driven forms
  * No unnecessary RxJS complexity
  * No deprecated Angular APIs

# Architecture Rules

* **This repository:** features live under `src/app/<feature>/` (e.g. `exercises/`). Typical contents: route components in their own folders (e.g. `exercise-list/`, `exercise-form/`), plus `*.service.ts`, `*.model.ts`, `*.routes.ts` at the feature root. Use `src/app/shared/ui/`, `src/app/shared/utils/`, and `src/app/core/` for cross-cutting code.
* **Conceptual model** (when structuring or naming new work): feature modules mirror `components/`, `pages/`, `services/`, `models/`—prefer matching the **existing** feature’s layout over introducing a second pattern.
* Separation of concerns:

  * UI (components)
  * State / logic (containers/services)
  * Data models (interfaces)

# Forms Standard (VERY IMPORTANT)

* ALWAYS use Reactive Forms
* Use `FormBuilder` for creating forms
* Strongly type form models
* Validation:

  * Define validators in component
  * Show error messages clearly in UI
  * Do not handle validation in template logic

* Form structure must be consistent across app

# UI System Rules (STRICT)

* Always reuse shared UI from `src/app/shared/ui/` (barrel: `shared/ui/index.ts`). **Mandatory** components:

  * Actions → `app-button` (wraps `p-button`; do not use raw `p-button` in features)
  * Text field → `app-input` (except inside `p-iconfield`, where native `pInputText` is required)
  * Select → `app-select` (`p-select` only; never `p-dropdown`)
  * Field chrome → `app-form-field`
  * Page header → `app-page-header`
  * List filter row → `app-filter-bar`
  * Data table → `app-data-table`
  * Panel / card shell → `app-ui-panel-card`

* **Target patterns for list screens:** centralize filters and tables in shared components (e.g. filter bar + data table) when they exist—**extend** those components instead of duplicating markup per page.
* Do NOT duplicate UI patterns across features
* Extend existing shared components instead of recreating them
* **Inconsistent styling** → change **`shared/ui`**, not individual pages

# Design system & Figma (STRICT)

* **Primary brand color is blue** (`--inv-primary-*`, PrimeNG `semantic.primary`). **Do not use purple** for primary UI.
* **Tokens:** `src/styles.scss` (`:root`), **PrimeNG preset:** `src/app/core/prime-ng.config.ts`, **Tailwind:** `tailwind.config.js` (`inv.*` colors, spacing, radii).
* **No arbitrary hex** in feature code—use **`var(--inv-*)`** or Tailwind **`text-inv-*` / `bg-inv-*` / `border-inv-*` / `bg-inv-surface-base`**.
* **Figma MCP** workflow, MCP as source of truth, and color rules: see **`.cursor/rules/figma-design-system.mdc`** (load for Figma-driven or token work).

# Styling Rules

* Use TailwindCSS for:

  * Layout (flex, grid)
  * Spacing (gap, padding, margin)
  * Responsive layout and visibility via breakpoint prefixes (`sm:`, `md:`, `lg:`)—see **Responsive UI**
  * **Design-token colors and type** via `inv-*` utilities (`text-inv-grey-500`, `bg-inv-surface-base`, etc.)—see `tailwind.config.js`

* Do NOT:

  * Write large custom CSS files
  * Use inline styles (except rare dynamic non-color values where unavoidable)
  * Override PrimeNG styles unnecessarily

* Keep UI:

  * Minimal
  * Clean
  * Consistent

# Layout Rules

* Use flex + gap for layout
* Follow 8px spacing system:

  * `gap-2` (8px)
  * `gap-4` (16px)
  * `gap-6` (24px)

* Maintain consistent spacing across all screens

# Responsive UI (STRICT)

* Every screen and shared component must work from small viewports through desktop: no horizontal overflow, readable text, tappable targets on touch devices.
* Prefer Tailwind responsive prefixes (`sm:`, `md:`, `lg:`) for layout shifts; use flex/grid with wrapping and `min-w-0` where flex children truncate or scroll.
* Tables and dense data: enable horizontal scroll on narrow widths, stack filter/toolbars vertically on small screens, or use patterns PrimeNG supports for responsive tables—do not assume a fixed desktop width.
* Side navigation, drawers, and page shells must collapse or adapt on narrow breakpoints consistently with the rest of the app.
* Test mentally (and in the browser) at least mobile-width and desktop-width; avoid fixed pixel widths that break small screens.

# Performance & Loading (STRICT)

* Prefer **lazy-loaded routes** for features so initial bundle stays small and first paint is fast.
* Use **`@defer`** (or lazy `import()`) for heavy below-the-fold or optional UI when it fits; show placeholders or skeletons during load.
* Avoid blocking the first render: show shell + loading/skeleton states for async data instead of blank screens; use `OnPush` and signals to limit change detection work.
* Do not load large dependencies eagerly on every page; split by route or defer where possible.
* Images and media: lazy loading and appropriate sizing; avoid huge unoptimized assets in the critical path.
* Keep lists efficient: virtual scrolling or pagination for large datasets when the feature warrants it; avoid rendering thousands of DOM nodes at once.

# PrimeNG Rules

* Table → `p-table`
* Select / dropdown → `p-select` (this project uses PrimeNG v21+; avoid legacy `p-dropdown` unless migrating old code)
* Button → `p-button`
* Tag → `p-tag`
* Input → `pInputText` / `p-inputTextarea` (directive or component per docs)
* Always use PrimeNG components instead of raw HTML where a component exists
* Configure components properly instead of hacking styles

# Component Design Rules

* Keep components:

  * Small
  * Focused
  * Reusable

* Use Smart vs Dumb pattern:

  * Smart (container): handles API, state
  * Dumb (presentational): UI only

* Use `@Input` and `@Output` clearly
* Avoid tight coupling between components

# State & Data Handling

* Use services for API calls
* Do not call APIs directly in templates
* Keep state simple (avoid over-engineering)
* Use signals or simple RxJS patterns where needed
* Avoid unnecessary global state

# Code Quality Rules

* Code must be:

  * Clean
  * Readable
  * Maintainable
  * Production-ready

* Naming:

  * Methods: verb-based (`getExercises`, `createExercise`)
  * Variables: descriptive and clear

* Avoid:

  * Magic values (use constants/enums)
  * Dead code
  * Console logs

# File Naming Convention

* Use kebab-case for files
* Examples:

  * `exercise-list.component.ts`
  * `exercise-form.component.ts`
  * `exercise.service.ts`
  * `exercise.model.ts`

# UI Consistency Rules

* All pages should follow the same layout pattern:

  * Page header (shared: `app-page-header`)
  * Filter bar (shared component when available)
  * Content (`p-table` / shared data table wrapper, or reactive form)

* Do not redesign layouts per page
* Maintain consistent:

  * Spacing
  * Alignment
  * Component usage

# When Generating Code

* Follow existing project structure strictly
* Match naming conventions already used in this repo
* Reuse existing shared components whenever possible
* Always:

  1. Reuse
  2. Keep consistency
  3. Optimize for maintainability

# Anti-Patterns (DO NOT DO)

* Do not use template-driven forms
* Do not mix UI frameworks
* Do not duplicate UI logic
* Do not create large monolithic components
* Do not use inline styles
* Do not break design consistency
* Do not ship layouts that only work at one breakpoint or that ignore touch/small screens
* Do not block initial navigation on optional data or huge synchronous work on the main thread

# Goal

Build a scalable, maintainable Angular admin dashboard with:

* Clean architecture
* Consistent UI that is **responsive** across viewports
* **Fast perceived load**: lazy routes, deferral where appropriate, lean initial bundles
* Reusable components
* Modern Angular best practices
